thread.title: Fever fall to Lynx on buzzer-beater in WNBA Finals Game 3

title: Fever fall to Lynx on buzzer-beater in WNBA Finals Game 3
text:
A dejected Indiana Fever Tamika Catchings (24) late in the second half of their game. The Indiana Fever play the Minnesota Lynx in Game #3 of the WNBA Finals Friday, October 9, 2015, evening at Bankers Life Fieldhouse. (Photo: Matt_Kryger/The_Star)
3 CONNECT 3 TWEET LINKEDIN 1 COMMENT EMAIL MORE Maya Moore sank a 3-pointer as time expired, lifting the Minnesota Lynx over the Indiana Fever 80-77 Friday night and within one victory of a WNBA championship.
Moore scored 24 points before a crowd of 16,322 at Bankers Life Fieldhouse. The Lynx took a 2-1 lead in the best-of-five WNBA Finals.
Game 4 will be Sunday at Bankers Life Fieldhouse (8:30 p.m., ESPN2). Game 5, if necessary, will be Wednesday at Minneapolis.
Shenise Johnson led the Fever with 17 points. Briann January added 15 points and eight assists, and Marissa Coleman scored 14 points.
Tamika Catchings had 10 points and eight rebounds.
The Lynx led by five early in the fourth quarter before the Fever rallied to go ahead, 75-73. Catchings made a 3-pointer to tie it at 73, then stole the ball. She missed her layup, but after an inbounds pass, Erlana Larkins followed with a layup on a give-and-go from January.
January’s pull-up jump shot expanded the Fever’s lead to 77-74 with 2:02 left, but Lynx guard Renee Montgomery responded with a 3-pointer to tie it at 77 with 1:11 on the clock.
January missed a potential go-ahead jumper, and the miss was rebounded by Larkins, who threw away the ball. Montgomery missed, too, and the Fever called timeout with the score tied and 25.2 seconds remaining. The Fever called another timeout with 16.8 on the clock.

You may also like these photo galleries: Replay Autoplay Show Thumbnails Show Captions Last Slide Next Slide Johnson’s 3-point attempt was deflected, and the ball reverted to the Lynx with 1.7 on the clock. Moore had just enough time to shoot the game-winner.
As they did in Game 2, the Lynx took control during the third quarter and led 59-57 going into the fourth. Moore picked up a fourth foul with 8:39 left in the third quarter but stayed in the game for precious minutes. The Lynx ramped up their defense and forced the Fever far out on the floor to begin possessions.
The Fever went on a 9-0 run late in the second quarter to erase what had been a seven-point deficit and took a 42-38 halftime lead. During that spurt, Catchings made two free throws and assisted on baskets by Coleman and Johnson.
The Lynx had previously led 26-19, 28-21 and 30-23 -- their largest margins of the series.
The Lynx were hampered by the absence of Moore, who went to the bench after a third foul with 8:33 left in the second quarter. The Lynx preserved their lead until the late in the half, when the Fever pounced on turnovers and surged ahead.
Johnson scored 11 points in the second quarter and had 14 at the half. In the half, the Fever shot 6-of-11 on 3s – featuring January’s 3-of-4 – and had 11 assists on 16 field goals. The Fever shot 69 percent (9-of-13) in the second quarter.
The Fever were outrebounded 17-12 in the first half but shot 53 percent to Minnesota’s 48 percent.
Etc. The Fever honored retired players Katie Douglas and Tammy Sutton-Brown, who were on the 2012 championship team. … The playoff game was Catchings’ 65th, a WNBA record. … Over the past five seasons, Minnesota is 3-4 against the Fever in the postseason and 25-5 against all other opponents.
